Askham Bog.label: Askham Bog
Askham Bog.description: Askham Bog is an area of peat bog in the Vale of York in North Yorkshire, England, south of the city of York, north of Copmanthorpe and close to Askham Bryan and Askham Richard. Wikipedia

Colwell Bay.label: Colwell Bay
Colwell Bay.description: Colwell Bay is a bay in the west of the Isle of Wight. It is located between the towns of Totland and Yarmouth. Wikipedia

Eastern Isles.label: Eastern Isles
Eastern Isles.description: The Eastern Isles are a group of twelve small uninhabited islands within the Isles of Scilly Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, part of the Scilly Heritage Coast and a Site of Special Scientific Interest ... Wikipedia

Sound Heath.label: Sound Heath
Sound Heath.description: Sound Heath, also known as Sound Common, is an area of common land in Sound, near Nantwich in Cheshire, England, which includes heathland, grassland, scrub, woodland and wetland habitats. Wikipedia

Studland and Godlingston Heath NNR.label: Studland and Godlingston Heath National Nature Reserve
Studland and Godlingston Heath NNR.description: The Studland and Godlingston Heaths NNR is located on the Isle of Purbeck in the English county of Dorset. It borders Studland Bay on the south side of Poole Harbour, between the settlements of Swanage and Sandbanks. Wikipedia

The Wilderness SSSI, Isle of Wight.label: The Wilderness SSSI, Isle of Wight
The Wilderness SSSI, Isle of Wight.description: The Wilderness is a 12.6 hectare Site of special scientific interest which is west of Godshill on the Isle of Wight. Wikipedia

Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly.label: Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly
Western Rocks, Isles of Scilly.description: The Western Rocks are a group of uninhabited islands and rocks in the south–western part of the Isles of Scilly, United Kingdom, and are renowned for the numerous shipwrecks in the area and the nearby Bishop Rock lighthouse. Wikipedia

Mottey Meadows.label: Mottey Meadows
Mottey Meadows.description: Mottey Meadows National Nature Reserve consists of a series of alluvial flood meadows near the village of Wheaton Aston in Staffordshire, England. The meadows have been managed for hay making for many centuries. Wikipedia

Arreton Down.label: Arreton Down
Arreton Down.description: Arreton Down is a 29.77 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest on the Isle of Wight, originally notified in 1979 for its geological interest and then renotified in 1987, but for its biological interest only. Wikipedia

Barns Batch Spinney.label: Barns Batch Spinney
Barns Batch Spinney.description: Barns Batch Spinney is a 0.06-hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Dundry, North Somerset, notified in 1987. Wikipedia

Bickley Wood.label: Bickley Wood
Bickley Wood.description: Bickley Wood is a 9.5 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest just north of River Avon, near the village of Longwell Green, Bristol, notified in 1988. Wikipedia

Bodkin Hazel Wood.label: Bodkin Hazel Wood
Bodkin Hazel Wood.description: Bodkin Hazel Wood is a 10.62 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest, just south of the village of Hawkesbury Upton in South Gloucestershire, notified in 1974. Wikipedia

Ham Green SSSI.label: Ham Green SSSI
Ham Green SSSI.description:
Ham Green SSSI is a 1.1 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Ham Green, North Somerset, notified in 1990.
This is a Geological Conservation Review site. Wikipedia

Lower Bostraze and Leswidden SSSI.label: Lower Bostraze and Leswidden SSSI
Lower Bostraze and Leswidden SSSI.description: Lower Bostraze And Leswidden SSSI is a biological Site of Special Scientific Interest, located on the Penwith Peninsula, Cornwall, a little to the east of St Just, approximately 8 km west of Penzance. Wikipedia

Lower Woods.label: Lower Woods
Lower Woods.description: Lower Woods is a 280.1-hectare biological and geological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Wickwar, South Gloucestershire, notified in 1966 and renotified in 1985. Wikipedia

Monkswood Valley.label: Monkswood Valley
Monkswood Valley.description: Monkswood Valley is a 30.7 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Cold Ashton, South Gloucestershire, notified in 1990. Wikipedia

Parkhurst Forest.label: Parkhurst Forest
Parkhurst Forest.description:
Parkhurst Forest is a woodland to the north-west of Newport, Isle of Wight, England.
The site is partly a site of special scientific interest. It consists of both ancient woodland, relict heathland and plantation woodland. Wikipedia

Quants Reserve.label: Quants Reserve
Quants Reserve.description:
Quants Reserve is a nature reserve north west of Burnworthy in Somerset, England.
It consists of a grassland clearing in a forestry plantation. Wikipedia

Soudley Ponds.label: Soudley Ponds
Soudley Ponds.description: Lying close to the village of Soudley in the Forest of Dean, west Gloucestershire, Soudley Ponds, also known as Sutton Ponds, comprise four linked man-made ponds lined in succession through the narrow ... Wikipedia

Severn Estuary.label: Severn Estuary
Severn Estuary.description: The Severn Estuary is the estuary of the River Severn, the longest river in Great Britain. It is at the mouth of four major rivers being the Severn, Wye, Usk and Avon and other smaller rivers. Wikipedia

Bridgwater Bay.label: Bridgwater Bay
Bridgwater Bay.description: Bridgwater Bay is on the Bristol Channel, 5 kilometres north of Bridgwater in Somerset, England at the mouth of the River Parrett and the end of the River Parrett Trail. Wikipedia

Derwent Ings.label: Derwent Ings
Derwent Ings.description: Derwent Ings is a Site of Special Scientific Interest in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England. Derwent Ings is of international significance and has been designated a Wetland of International Importance ... Wikipedia

Westhay Moor.label: Westhay Moor
Westhay Moor.description: Westhay Moor is a 513.7 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest 2.5 km north-east of Westhay village and 4 km from Wedmore in Somerset, England, notified in 1971. Wikipedia

Barnsley Warren.label: Barnsley Warren
Barnsley Warren.description: Barnsley Warren is a 61.3-hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Gloucestershire, notified in 1954 and renotified in 1984. The site is also a Nature Conservation Review site. Wikipedia

Littledean Hall.label: Littledean Hall
Littledean Hall.description: Littledean Hall is a country house in the village of Littledean, Gloucestershire, England. It is reputedly one of the most haunted houses in England and is thought to be the oldest house in the United Kingdom which is still occupied. Wikipedia

Midger.label: Midger
Midger.description: Midger is a 65.7-hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest straddling the border of Gloucestershire and South Gloucestershire, notified in 1966 and renotified in 1984. Wikipedia

Sylvan House Barn.label: Sylvan House Barn
Sylvan House Barn.description: Sylvan House Barn is a 0.005-hectare stone built barn near the village of St Briavels, in the Forest of Dean, Gloucestershire. Because of its breeding bats, the site was notified as a biological Site of Special Scientific Interest in 1995. Wikipedia

Wainlode Cliff.label: Wainlode Cliff
Wainlode Cliff.description: Wainlode Cliff is a 1.3 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Gloucestershire, notified in 1954. It overlooks Hasfield Ham. Wikipedia

Godrevy Head to St Agnes.label: Godrevy Head to St Agnes
Godrevy Head to St Agnes.description: Godrevy Head to St Agnes is a coastal Site of Special Scientific Interest in north Cornwall, England, UK, noted for both its biological and geological characteristics. Wikipedia

Boscastle to Widemouth.label: Boscastle to Widemouth
Boscastle to Widemouth.description: Boscastle to Widemouth is a coastal Site of Special Scientific Interest in Cornwall, England, noted for its biological and geological characteristics. Wikipedia

St Austell Clay Pits.label: St Austell Clay Pits
St Austell Clay Pits.description: St Austell Clay Pits are a group of locations within active china clay quarries that form a single Site of Special Scientific Interest and Special Area of Conservation, noted for its biological characteristics, in central Cornwall, England. Wikipedia

Alvecote Pools.label: Alvecote Pools
Alvecote Pools.description: Alvecote Pools is a Site of Special Scientific Interest and nature reserve situated alongside the River Anker, adjacent to the hamlet of Alvecote on the border of Warwickshire and Staffordshire in England. Wikipedia

Asham Wood.label: Asham Wood
Asham Wood.description:
Asham Wood is a 140.6-hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest near Downhead in the Mendip Hills, Somerset, notified in 1963.
Asham Wood is the largest and most diverse of the ancient semi-natural woods in the Mendips. Wikipedia

Ashfield Brick Pits.label: Ashfield Brick Pits
Ashfield Brick Pits.description: Ashfield Brick Pits is a 0.6 hectare geological site of Special Scientific Interest in South Yorkshire. The site was notified in 1955. Wikipedia

Banwell Caves.label: Banwell Caves
Banwell Caves.description: Banwell Caves are a 1.7-hectare geological and biological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Banwell, North Somerset, England notified in 1963. Wikipedia

Banwell Ochre Caves.label: Banwell Ochre Caves
Banwell Ochre Caves.description: Banwell Ochre Caves are a 12.46-hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Banwell, North Somerset, notified in 1983. Wikipedia

Ben Knowle.label: Ben Knowle
Ben Knowle.description: Ben Knowle is a 1.5 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Somerset, notified in 1984. Wikipedia

Black Down and Sampford Commons.label: Black Down and Sampford Commons
Black Down and Sampford Commons.description: Black Down and Sampford Commons is a 155.2-hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Devon and Somerset, notified in 1952. Wikipedia

Berkswell Marsh.label: Berkswell Marsh
Berkswell Marsh.description: Berkswell Marsh is a 7.5 hectare biological site of Special Scientific Interest in the West Midlands. The site was notified in 1991 under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. Wikipedia

Briddlesford Copses.label: Briddlesford Copses
Briddlesford Copses.description: Briddleford Copses is a 167.2 hectare Site of Special Scientific Interest and Special Area of Conservation which is south of Wootton Bridge on the Isle of Wight in Britain. Wikipedia

Briggins Moor.label: Briggins Moor
Briggins Moor.description: Briggins Moor is a 15.3 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Somerset, notified in 1994. The site is south of Dulverton and close to the border with Devon. Wikipedia

Burledge Hill.label: Burledge Hill
Burledge Hill.description: Burledge Hill is on the southern edge of the village of Bishop Sutton, Somerset, England. It is the site of a Site of Special Scientific Interest and an univallate Iron Age hillfort. Wikipedia

Clayhanger Marsh.label: Clayhanger Marsh
Clayhanger Marsh.description: Clayhanger Marsh is a 23.8 hectare biological site of Special Scientific Interest in the West Midlands. The site was notified in 1986 under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981. It is located to the north of Walsall. Wikipedia

Cogley Wood.label: Cogley Wood
Cogley Wood.description:
Cogley Wood is a 60.7 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest east of Bruton in Somerset, notified in 1987.
The name is believed to be from Cock ley meaning a clearing with birds. Wikipedia

Cloford Quarry.label: Cloford Quarry
Cloford Quarry.description: Cloford Quarry is a 39.92-hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest to the south of the A361 approximately 350 metres north of the hamlet of Cloford and 1 kilometre west of Nunney on the Mendip Hills in Somerset. Wikipedia

Rosenannon Downs.label: Rosenannon Downs
Rosenannon Downs.description: Rosenannon Downs is a nature reserve in central Cornwall, England, UK, being designated Rosenannon Bog and Downs Site of Special Scientific Interest, noted for its biological characteristics. Wikipedia

Compton Down.label: Compton Down
Compton Down.description: Compton Down is a hill on the Isle of Wight just to the east of Freshwater Bay. It is part of the chalk ridge which forms the "backbone" of the Isle of Wight. It runs east to west, is approximately 3 miles long and is predominantly grass downland. Wikipedia

Compton Martin Ochre Mine.label: Compton Martin Ochre Mine
Compton Martin Ochre Mine.description: Compton Martin Ochre Mine is a 0.85 hectare geological and biological Site of Special Scientific Interest located on the north side of the Mendip Hills, immediately south west of Compton Martin village, Somerset, notified in 1988. Wikipedia

Curry and Hay Moors.label: Curry and Hay Moors
Curry and Hay Moors.description:
Curry and Hay Moors is a 472.8 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Somerset, notified in 1992.
Curry and Hay Moors form part of the complex of grazing marshes known as the Somerset Levels and Moors. Wikipedia

Dunster Park and Heathlands.label: Dunster Park and Heathlands
Dunster Park and Heathlands.description: Dunster Park and Heathlands is a 466.6 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest in Somerset, notified in 2000. Wikipedia

Emborough Quarries.label: Emborough Quarries
Emborough Quarries.description: Emborough Quarries is a 1 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest at Emborough in the Mendip Hills, Somerset, notified in 1971. Wikipedia

Cook's Wood Quarry.label: Cook's Wood Quarry
Cook's Wood Quarry.description:
Cook's Wood Quarry is a 0.8 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest near Stoke St Michael on the Mendip Hills in Somerset, notified in 1988.
This is a Geological Conservation Review Site. Wikipedia

Fens Pools.label: Fens Pools
Fens Pools.description: Fens Pools is a 37.6 hectare biological site of Special Scientific Interest in the West Midlands. The site was notified in 1989 under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 and is currently managed by the Country Trust. Wikipedia

Doulton's Claypit.label: Doulton's Claypit
Doulton's Claypit.description: Doulton's Claypit is a 3.3 hectare geological site of Special Scientific Interest in the West Midlands. The site was notified in 1986 under the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 and is currently managed by the Country Trust. Wikipedia

Ge-mare Farm Fields.label: Ge-mare Farm Fields
Ge-mare Farm Fields.description: Ge-mare Farm Fields is a 4.1 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest near Holford on the Quantock Hills in Somerset, notified in 1988. Wikipedia

Glenthorne.label: Glenthorne High School
Glenthorne.description:
Glenthorne High School is a non-selective coeducational secondary school and sixth form with academy status, located in the Sutton area of the London Borough of Sutton, England.
The school was first established in 1933 on Glastonbury Road in Sutton. Wikipedia

Greatwood And Cliff Copses SSSI.label: Greatwood And Cliff Copses SSSI
Greatwood And Cliff Copses SSSI.description: Greatwood And Cliff Copses are two wooded areas totalling 16.3 hectares which are a Site of special scientific interest to the southwest of Shanklin. The site was notified in 1986 for its biological features. Wikipedia

Lamb Leer.label: Lamb Leer
Lamb Leer.description: Lamb Leer is a 14.59 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest between East Harptree and Priddy in the Mendip Hills, Somerset, notified in 1983. Wikipedia

Kingley Vale National Nature Reserve.label: Kingley Vale National Nature Reserve
Kingley Vale National Nature Reserve.description: The Kingley Vale National Nature Reserve is a National Nature Reserve near Chichester, West Sussex in southern England, and is part of the South Downs. It covers an area of 160 hectares. Wikipedia

Maes Down.label: Maes Down
Maes Down.description: Maes Down is a 0.2 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest between Shepton Mallet and Stoney Stratton in Somerset, notified in 1985. It is a Geological Conservation Review site. Wikipedia

Lindrick Golf Club.label: Lindrick Golf Club
Lindrick Golf Club.description: Lindrick Golf Club is a golf course in South Yorkshire and is also a site of special scientific interest. The SSSI covers 22.0 hectares and was designated for its biological interest. The site was notified in 1987. Wikipedia

Northpark Copse.label: Northpark Copse
Northpark Copse.description: Northpark Copse is a 9.9 hectare Site of special scientific interest which is east of Shalfleet. The site was notified in 1986 for its biological features. Wikipedia

Purn Hill.label: Purn Hill
Purn Hill.description: Purn Hill is a 6.1 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Bleadon, Somerset, notified in 1990. The site is a small promontory of Carboniferous Limestone projecting southward from the main Mendip ridge. Wikipedia

Old Ironstone Works, Mells.label: Old Ironstone Works, Mells
Old Ironstone Works, Mells.description: Old Iron Works, Mells is a 0.25 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest, in the Wadbury Valley, south of the village of Mells in Somerset, notified in 1987. Wikipedia

Shapwick Heath.label: Shapwick Heath
Shapwick Heath.description: Shapwick Heath is a 394.0-hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest and National Nature Reserve between Shapwick and Westhay in Somerset, notified in 1967. It is part of the Brue Valley Living Landscape conservation project. Wikipedia

Sharpham Moor Plot.label: Sharpham Moor Plot
Sharpham Moor Plot.description: Sharpham Moor Plot is a 0.5-hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest at Sharpham in Somerset, UK, notified in 1967. Wikipedia

Maesbury Railway Cutting.label: Maesbury Railway Cutting
Maesbury Railway Cutting.description:
Maesbury Railway Cutting is a 2 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest between East Horrington and Gurney Slade in Somerset, notified in 1995.
It was part of the Somerset and Dorset Joint Railway. Wikipedia

Shiplate Slait.label: Shiplate Slait
Shiplate Slait.description: Shiplate Slait is a 33.9 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest near the village of Loxton, within the Mendip Hills Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, North Somerset, notified in 1987. Wikipedia

Snowdon Hill Quarry.label: Snowdon Hill Quarry
Snowdon Hill Quarry.description: Snowdon Hill Quarry is a 0.6 hectare geological Site of Special Scientific Interest on the western outskirts of Chard in Somerset, notified in 1963. Wikipedia

St. Dunstan's Well Catchment.label: St. Dunstan's Well Catchment
St. Dunstan's Well Catchment.description: St. Dunstan's Well Catchment is a Site of Special Scientific Interest, covering 39.8 hectares near Stoke St Michael in the Mendip Hills, Somerset, notified in 1967. It is of both geological and biological significance. Wikipedia

Southey and Gotleigh Moors.label: Southey and Gotleigh Moors
Southey and Gotleigh Moors.description:
Southey and Gotleigh Moors is an 81.3 hectare biological Site of Special Scientific Interest on the Blackdown Hills in Somerset, notified in 1988.
Southey and Gotleigh Moors is a mosaic of valley mire, acid-marsh grassland and alder-birch carr. Wikipedia
